{
  "texts": [
    "This extensive exploration is crucial for WCET estimation, as it increases the likelihood of identifying true worst-case scenarios across a diverse range of system states and behaviors.As shown in Table 5.2, GA ED outperforms GA E as the average WCET by inputs generated using GA ED is 65.91 Millisecond (74%) larger than the WCET of GA E for the CD case study.",
    "To statistically assess the significance of the differences observed between the two GA versions, a t-test [118] was applied on the average values obtained.",
    "This test is appropriate for comparing the means from two related samples of scores, such as the performance measures of the GA versions in this study.The t-test is a statistical method used to compare the means of two samples to determine if they are significantly different from each other using the following formula:t = x1 -x2 s 2 1 n 1 + s 2 2 n 2(5.1)• x1 and x2 are the sample means of the two groups being compared.• s 2 1 and s 2 2 are the variances of the two samples.• n 1 and n 2 are the sizes of the two samples.The t-value calculated from this formula is then compared to a critical value from the t-distribution to determine if the difference between the means is statistically significant.",
    "If the absolute value of the calculated t-value is greater than the critical value, it indicates that the difference between the sample means is unlikely to have occurred by chance, and therefore, the means are considered statistically different.",
    "By applying t-test on two GA versions based on the average amounts, p-value is 6.05 × 10 -6."
  ]
}